15. FAIR VALUE MEASUREMENT 

Fair value is the price that would be received upon the sale of an asset or paid upon the transfer of a liability in an orderly transaction between market participants at the measurement date and in the principal or most advantageous market for that asset or liability. The fair value should be calculated based on assumptions that market participants would use in pricing the asset or liability, not on assumptions specific to the entity. In addition, the fair value of liabilities should include consideration of non-performance risk, including the Company&#8217;s own credit risk. 

The Company applied ASC 820 &#8211; Fair Value Measurement, which provides guidance for using fair value to measure assets and liabilities by defining fair value and establishing the framework for measuring fair value. ASC 820 applies to financial and nonfinancial instruments that are measured and reported on a fair value basis. The three-level hierarchy of fair value measurements is based on whether the inputs to those measurements are observable or unobservable. Observable inputs reflect market data obtained from independent sources, while unobservable inputs reflect the Company&#8217;s market assumptions. The fair value hierarchy requires the use of observable market data when available and consists of the following levels: 

##TABLE_START &#9679; Level 1&#8212;Unadjusted inputs based on quoted markets for identical assets or liabilities. ##TABLE_END 

##TABLE_START &#9679; Level 2&#8212;Observable inputs, either direct or indirect, not including Level 1 measurements, corroborated by market data or based upon quoted prices in non-active markets. ##TABLE_END 

##TABLE_START &#9679; Level 3&#8212;Unobservable inputs that reflect management&#8217;s best assumptions of what market participants would use in valuing the asset or liability. ##TABLE_END 

The Company has included a tabular disclosure for financial assets and liabilities that are measured at fair value on a recurring basis in the consolidated balance sheets as of December 31, 2022 and 2021, respectively. 

